Data Analysis on Classifying the Severity of Genetic Mutations
¶

Overview
¶

The goal of my Capstone was to find a computational model to classify the severity of genetic mutations using the gene the mutation is on, the kind of variation, and the clinical evidence used to classify the mutation.

Data Obtained From a Kaggle.com Research Prediction Competion Included:

  1. Gene- the gene the genetic mutation was on (Ex. CBL, RUNX1)
  2. Variation- shows the specific amino acid change that caused the muation (Ex. Q249E means glutamic acid (E) was placed as the amino acid in the 249 codon instead of glutamine (Q))
  3. Text- clinical evidence in the form of text data

Step 2: Cleaning the Text Data
¶

Function to clean each cell of text:¶

In [7]:
#create a function that takes a cell string in the dataframe and cleans that cell (lowercase, no special characters or spacing) 
def clean(cellString):   
    
    #convert to lower case 
    cellString= cellString.lower() 
    
    #convert any special characters to a space 
    cellString = re.sub('[^a-zA-Z0-9\n\.]', ' ', cellString) 
    
    #convert any double spaces to a single space  
    cellString=re.sub('\s+', ' ', cellString)   
    
    #get rid of stop words (aka frequently occuring words)   
    stop_words= set(stopwords.words('english'))
    cleanedSentence=""
    for word in cellString.split():
        if not word in stop_words: 
            cleanedSentence= cleanedSentence+ str(word)+ " "
        
    return cleanedSentence

Create Train and Test Sets for our Models
¶

Train Test Concept:

  • Allow the model to run its algorithm on a random 80% of our data
  • Then apply this model to the rest of the 20% of the data and see how it performs

How To Split Data:

  1. Train Input- this includes the gene encoding, variation encoding, and text encoding used to predict the class of the genetic mutation
  2. Train Output- the class related to the train data
  3. Test Input- again the gene encoding, variation, and text encoding but for the test set
  4. Test Output- the corresponing class to the test data

Model 1: Decision Tree
¶

Splits data into nodes and subnodes based on similarities in gene, variation, and text in order to predict the class of the genetic mutation.

Simple Example of a Decision Tree https://www.researchgate.net/figure/An-example-of-a-simple-decision-tree_fig2_311614501

The Decision Tree Model for this data yields a 55% accuracy of predicting the correct class from 1-9 on severity of genetic mutation.¶

In [19]:

Model 3: Random Forest¶

Idea is similiar to Decision Tree, except random forest builds multiple decision trees and merges them together

https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2020/05/decision-tree-vs-random-forest-algorithm/

Random Forest yields a 60% accuracy rating on predicting the class (1-9) of genetic mutations.¶

Logistic Regression
¶

Logistic Regression tries to determine the linear relationship between gene, variation, and text encoding in order to predict class. Since this data is not binary and does not seem to possess a linear relationship, this regression is not too useful

https://miro.medium.com/max/725/1*QY3CSyA4BzAU6sEPFwp9ZQ.png

**Logistic Regressions yields a 33% accuarcy in predicting the class (1-9) of genetic mutations.

K Nearest Neighbor¶

K Nearest Neighbor predicts class by looking the the category of its nearest "neighbor" or closest data point

**K Nearest neighbor yields a 44% accuracy in predicting the class (1-9) of genetic mutation,

In [ ]:
